06155nam a22008415i 9780857455727DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20072007nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808574557277 a10.1515/97808574557272doi  a(DE-B1597)636372  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aGN36.O34 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a069.099522204aThe Future of Indigenous Museums :bPerspectives from the Southwest Pacific /ced. by Nick Stanley. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMuseums and Collections ;v100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tEditorial Preface -- tIntroduction Indigeneity and Museum Practice in the Southwest Pacific -- tPart I Island Melanesia -- t1 Resourcing Change: Fieldworkers, the Women’s Culture Project and the Vanuatu Cultural Centre -- t2 The Future of Indigenous Museums: The Solomon Islands Case -- t3 Dangerous Heritage: Southern New Ireland, the Museum and the Display of the Past -- t4 Memory, Violence and Representation in the Tjibaou Cultural Centre, New Caledonia -- t5 Tourism and Indigenous Curation of Culture in Lifou, New Caledonia -- tPart II Northern Australia -- t6 The Journey of the Stars: Gab Titui, a Cultural Centre for the Torres Strait -- t7 ‘Quite Another World of Aboriginal Life’: Indigenous People in an Evolving Museumscape -- tPart III New Guinea -- t8 The Papua New Guinea National Museum and Art Gallery as a Modern Haus Tumbuna -- t9 Moving the Centre: Christianity, the Longhouse and the Gogodala Cultural Centre -- t10 Indigenous Responses to Political and Economic Challenges: the Babek Bema Yoma at Teptep, Papua New Guinea -- t11 Can Museums become Indigenous? The Asmat Museum of Culture and Progress and Contemporary Papua -- tPart IV Reflections on the Future of Indigenous Museums -- t12 The Transformation of Cultural Centres in Papua New Guinea -- t13 The Theoretical Future of Indigenous Museums: Concept and Practice -- tNotes on Contributors -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIndigenous museums and cultural centres have sprung up across the developing world, and particularly in the Southwest Pacific. They derive from a number of motives, ranging from the commercial to the cultural political (and many combine both). A close study of this phenomenon is not only valuable for museological practice but, as has been argued, it may challenge our current bedrock assumptions about the very nature and purpose of the museum. This book looks to the future of museum practice through examining how museums have evolved particularly in the non-western world to incorporate the present and the future in the display of culture. Of particular concern is the uses to which historic records are put in the service of community development and cultural renaissance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aEthnological museums and collectionszOceania. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aBin Juda, Leilani, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBolton, Lissant, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDundon, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoana‘ota, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaraha, Sebastian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerle, Anita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKingston, Sean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKocher Schmid, Christin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 